  "body": "**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**\r\nPossibly both\r\n\r\n**What is the current behavior?**\r\nCurrently, error boundaries will not catch an error when passing props to a component.\r\nTL;DR : \r\n```\r\n<ErrorBoundary>\r\n    <SomeComponent evil={this.does.not.exist} />\r\n</ErrorBoundary>\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Paste the link to your JSFiddle (https://jsfiddle.net/Luktwrdm/) or CodeSandbox (https://codesandbox.io/s/new) example below:**\r\nI created a small public repository to show the current behavior.\r\nYou can find it here : https://github.com/ganzf/reactErrorBoundariesForInvalidProps\r\n\r\n**What is the expected behavior?**\r\nI wish to catch this kind of error. If there is some wrong code anywhere in the component rendering cycle (even when passing props) I wish to be able to control this error. In the current repository, the invalid code is obviously wrong and could be fixed by a developer. But what about more dynamic code such as `object[this.props.name]` ?\r\n\r\n**Which versions of React, and which browser / OS are affected by this issue? Did this work in previous versions of React?**\r\nreact 16.4.1\r\nreact-dom 16.4.1\r\nreact-scripts 1.1.4\r\n",
